insert into public.concepts
  (id, term, aliases, said, alias_list, status, one_liner, analogy, example, related, deeper, lens_pm, lens_eng, domain, priority, tags)
values
  ('goldlabels', 'Gold Labels', '', '', ARRAY['gold labels','gold standard labels','ground truth labels']::text[], 'Core', 'The answers you trust completely, usually because a careful human wrote them down.', 'The teacher’s answer key at the back of the book — the one everything else gets graded against.', 'Before scoring a support-bot, a team hand-labels 500 tickets with the “correct” category and treats those as gold.', '[{"text":"What you measure your model against.","id":"evals"},{"text":"The careful cousin of noisy auto-labeling.","id":"labeling"}]'::jsonb, 'Gold labels are the reference answers you assume are right, produced by expert humans or a trusted process. They’re expensive, so you rarely have many — which is exactly why people reach for weak supervision or synthetic data to fill the gap. If your gold set is itself wrong or biased, every number downstream inherits that flaw.', 'Your metrics are only as trustworthy as the gold set they’re scored against, so invest in getting a small clean one.', 'A curated, high-confidence labeled set used as ground truth for evaluation or as the seed for training.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('weaksupervision', 'Weak Supervision', '', '', ARRAY['weak supervision','weakly supervised']::text[], 'Rising', 'Label a mountain of data cheaply with rough rules instead of paying humans to do it all by hand.', 'Sorting mail by zip-code stamps instead of reading every envelope — fast, mostly right, occasionally wrong.', 'To flag toxic comments, you write a few keyword rules and treat their output as labels, then train on millions of examples.', '[{"text":"The cheap alternative to hand-made gold labels.","id":"goldlabels"},{"text":"Trades quality for scale.","id":"labeling"}]'::jsonb, 'Instead of one careful label per example, you combine many noisy signals — heuristics, keyword rules, existing models — and let their agreement stand in for truth. You get far more labeled data than humans could ever produce, at the cost of noise you have to model or tolerate. It shines when data is abundant but human labeling is the bottleneck.', 'A way to bootstrap a labeled dataset in days instead of months when perfect labels aren’t worth the wait.', 'Programmatic labeling from multiple noisy sources whose outputs are aggregated into training signals.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('activelearning', 'Active Learning', '', '', ARRAY['active learning']::text[], 'Core', 'Let the model pick which examples it’s most confused by, and label only those.', 'A student who studies the questions they keep getting wrong instead of re-reading the whole textbook.', 'A vision model flags the 200 images it’s least sure about; a human labels just those and accuracy jumps.', '[{"text":"Feeds a smaller, smarter gold set.","id":"goldlabels"},{"text":"Powers the loop in a data flywheel.","id":"dataflywheel"}]'::jsonb, 'Labeling is expensive, so active learning spends that budget where it helps most: on the examples the model is most uncertain about or that would most reduce its errors. You train, ask the model where it’s weak, label those, and repeat. Done well it reaches the same accuracy with a fraction of the labels.', 'Cuts labeling cost by focusing human effort on the examples that actually move the needle.', 'An iterative loop that selects high-uncertainty or high-information samples for labeling to maximize accuracy per label.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('dataflywheel', 'Data Flywheel', '', '', ARRAY['data flywheel','data flywheels']::text[], 'Rising', 'Users generate data that makes the product better, which attracts more users, which makes more data.', 'A snowball rolling downhill — each turn picks up more snow and rolls faster on its own.', 'Every correction a user makes to the autocomplete trains the next version, which more people then use and correct.', '[{"text":"Often fed by active learning.","id":"activelearning"},{"text":"Turns usage into training signal.","id":"humanfeedback"}]'::jsonb, 'The flywheel is a self-reinforcing loop: real usage produces data, the data improves the model, the better model draws more usage. The hard part is the first push — you need enough users before the wheel spins on its own — and building the pipes that turn messy real-world interactions into clean training signal.', 'A durable moat: competitors can copy your model but not your accumulating stream of real user data.', 'A closed loop where production interactions are logged, curated, and fed back into retraining.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('modelmerging', 'Model Merging', '', '', ARRAY['model merging','merged model']::text[], 'Rising', 'Blend two or more trained models into one by mixing their weights, no extra training needed.', 'Combining two recipes into a single dish by averaging the ingredient amounts.', 'A team merges a model good at coding with one good at chat and gets one that’s decent at both, for free.', '[{"text":"The simplest version is a model soup.","id":"modelsoup"},{"text":"Relies on weight averaging.","id":"weightaveraging"}]'::jsonb, 'Because models trained from the same starting point live in compatible weight spaces, you can often average or interpolate their parameters and get a model that inherits multiple skills. It’s startlingly cheap — no gradients, no data — but it only works when the models are close relatives, and results can be unpredictable.', 'A near-free way to combine capabilities without the cost of training a new model from scratch.', 'Combining independently fine-tuned checkpoints via weight-space arithmetic to fuse capabilities.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('modelsoup', 'Model Soup', '', '', ARRAY['model soup','model soups']::text[], 'Rising', 'Average the weights of several fine-tuned models into one that’s often better than any single one.', 'Blending many cooks’ versions of the same soup — the average tastes more balanced than any one pot.', 'You fine-tune the same model ten times with different settings, average all ten, and the soup beats the best individual run.', '[{"text":"A specific recipe for model merging.","id":"modelmerging"},{"text":"It’s weight averaging applied to fine-tunes.","id":"weightaveraging"}]'::jsonb, 'A model soup takes several models fine-tuned from the same base with different hyperparameters and simply averages their weights. Surprisingly, the average often generalizes better than picking the single best model, because averaging cancels out each run’s idiosyncratic errors. The catch: the ingredients must share a starting point or the soup curdles.', 'Squeezes more accuracy out of training runs you already paid for instead of throwing the losers away.', 'Uniform or greedy averaging of same-lineage fine-tuned weights to improve generalization.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('weightaveraging', 'Weight Averaging', '', '', ARRAY['weight averaging','averaged weights']::text[], 'Core', 'Take the numerical average of a model’s weights across runs or checkpoints to get a steadier model.', 'Averaging several thermometer readings to smooth out the jitter in any single one.', 'Instead of shipping the final training step, a team averages the last ten checkpoints and ships that smoother version.', '[{"text":"The mechanism behind model soups.","id":"modelsoup"},{"text":"A moving-average variant is EMA.","id":"ema"}]'::jsonb, 'Individual training snapshots bounce around the loss landscape; averaging their weights lands you in a flatter, more robust spot that tends to generalize better. It works across checkpoints of one run or across separate runs from the same base. The requirement is compatibility — you can’t meaningfully average models that started from different places.', 'A cheap post-processing trick that often buys a small, free accuracy bump before shipping.', 'Parameter-space averaging that lands in flatter minima with better generalization.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('ema', 'EMA', 'Exponential Moving Average', '', ARRAY['ema','exponential moving average']::text[], 'Core', 'A running average of the model’s weights that leans on recent steps but never forgets the past.', 'A rolling average of your daily spending — today counts most, but last week still nudges the number.', 'During training, an EMA copy of the weights is kept alongside the live one, and the smoother EMA version is what gets shipped.', '[{"text":"A time-weighted flavor of weight averaging.","id":"weightaveraging"},{"text":"Often paired with checkpoint averaging.","id":"checkpointaveraging"}]'::jsonb, 'EMA maintains a shadow copy of the weights updated as a decaying blend: mostly the previous average, slightly the newest step. This damps the noise of individual updates and usually produces a more stable, higher-quality model than the raw final weights. It costs almost nothing but a second copy of the parameters.', 'A standard, low-risk way to make the shipped model a bit more reliable than the raw training output.', 'A decayed running mean of parameters maintained during training, typically used for the evaluation weights.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('finetunevsprompt', 'Fine-tune vs Prompt', '', '', ARRAY['fine-tune vs prompt','fine-tuning vs prompting','finetune vs prompt']::text[], 'Core', 'The recurring choice: teach the model new behavior by retraining it, or just by asking better in the prompt.', 'Sending an employee to a training course versus writing them a really clear instruction note.', 'A team wants consistent JSON output; they try a detailed prompt first, and only fine-tune once prompting hits its ceiling.', '[{"text":"One side of the trade-off.","id":"finetuning"},{"text":"The other side.","id":"promptengineering"},{"text":"Prompting leans on in-context learning.","id":"incontextlearning"}]'::jsonb, 'Prompting is fast, free to change, and reversible, but every request pays the token cost and behavior can drift. Fine-tuning bakes the behavior in — cheaper at inference, more consistent — but it’s slow to iterate and risks forgetting other skills. The rule of thumb: exhaust prompting first, fine-tune when you need consistency, lower latency, or behavior prompting can’t reach.', 'Prompting to validate an idea quickly; fine-tuning once the behavior is proven and volume justifies the cost.', 'A trade between updating weights (durable, costly to iterate) and steering via context (flexible, per-request cost).', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('overfittoeval', 'Overfit to Eval', '', '', ARRAY['overfit to eval','overfitting to the eval','teaching to the test']::text[], 'Rising', 'Tuning a model until it aces your test set while quietly getting worse at everything else.', 'Memorizing last year’s exam paper — you nail that test and learn nothing useful.', 'A team keeps tweaking prompts to raise a benchmark score, then finds the model got worse on real user questions.', '[{"text":"A close relative of overfitting.","id":"overfitting"},{"text":"Why you keep a fresh holdout.","id":"holdout"},{"text":"Worsened by train-test leakage.","id":"traintestleakage"}]'::jsonb, 'When you make many decisions based on one evaluation set, you slowly fit to its quirks rather than to the real task — the benchmark rises while true quality stalls or drops. It’s subtle because the number keeps going up. Defenses include held-out sets you look at rarely, rotating fresh evals, and judging on live traffic.', 'A rising benchmark can be a mirage; protect a private eval you don’t optimize against so you know what’s real.', 'Metric inflation from repeated selection against a fixed eval set; mitigate with held-out and rotating evaluations.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('traintestleakage', 'Train-Test Leakage', 'Data Leakage', '', ARRAY['train-test leakage','data leakage','test set leakage']::text[], 'Core', 'When test answers sneak into training, so the model looks brilliant on a test it has secretly already seen.', 'Grading a student on questions they were accidentally handed the night before.', 'A web-scraped training set turns out to contain the exact benchmark questions, and the reported score is meaningless.', '[{"text":"A cause of overfitting to eval.","id":"overfittoeval"},{"text":"Related to dataset contamination.","id":"datacontamination"},{"text":"Why you hold out clean data.","id":"holdout"}]'::jsonb, 'Leakage happens whenever information from the test set — the exact examples, or features derived from them — is present at training time. The model memorizes rather than generalizes, so evaluation numbers are inflated and collapse in the real world. With web-scale training data, accidental contamination of public benchmarks is a constant, hard-to-detect risk.', 'A leaked benchmark tells you nothing; always ask whether the eval data could have been in training.', 'Contamination of the evaluation set into training data, producing optimistic and non-generalizing metrics.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('checkpointaveraging', 'Checkpoint Averaging', '', '', ARRAY['checkpoint averaging','averaged checkpoints']::text[], 'Core', 'Average several saved snapshots from a single training run into one steadier final model.', 'Blending a few photos of a moving subject to cancel the blur and get one sharp shot.', 'Rather than shipping the last step, a team averages the final five checkpoints and gets a small, free quality gain.', '[{"text":"A specific use of weight averaging.","id":"weightaveraging"},{"text":"The streaming version is EMA.","id":"ema"},{"text":"Operates on saved checkpoints.","id":"checkpoint"}]'::jsonb, 'Late in training the weights oscillate around a good region rather than settling exactly. Averaging several nearby checkpoints lands you in a flatter, more robust center of that region, which usually generalizes a touch better than any single snapshot. It’s a standard, near-zero-cost finishing move.', 'A no-downside trick to slightly improve the final model from runs you already completed.', 'Averaging parameters of consecutive checkpoints from one run to reduce oscillation-driven variance.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('continuallearning', 'Continual Learning', 'Lifelong Learning', '', ARRAY['continual learning','lifelong learning','incremental learning']::text[], 'Rising', 'Teaching a model new things over time without making it forget what it already knew.', 'Adding new recipes to a chef’s repertoire without them suddenly forgetting how to make the old ones.', 'A support model needs this quarter’s product updates added on top, but must keep answering last year’s questions correctly.', '[{"text":"Fights catastrophic forgetting.","id":"catastrophicforgetting"},{"text":"Often uses a replay buffer.","id":"replaybuffer"},{"text":"Overlaps with continued pretraining.","id":"continuedpretraining"}]'::jsonb, 'The core tension is stability versus plasticity: learn new information fast enough to stay current, but not so aggressively that you overwrite old knowledge — the dreaded catastrophic forgetting. Techniques include replaying old data, freezing parts of the network, and adding small adapters. Truly seamless continual learning remains an open problem.', 'The dream of updating a model with fresh knowledge without a full, expensive retrain — with real trade-offs today.', 'Sequential training on new data while preserving prior performance, balancing plasticity against forgetting.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('domainadaptation', 'Domain Adaptation', '', '', ARRAY['domain adaptation','domain adapting']::text[], 'Core', 'Taking a model trained on one kind of data and adjusting it to work well on a different kind.', 'A driver who knows city streets taking a short course before driving a truck on mountain roads.', 'A general chat model is adapted on medical notes so it handles clinical shorthand instead of stumbling on it.', '[{"text":"A form of transfer learning.","id":"transferlearning"},{"text":"Often done via fine-tuning.","id":"finetuning"},{"text":"Or continued pretraining.","id":"continuedpretraining"}]'::jsonb, 'A model performs best on data resembling what it trained on; move it to a new domain — legal, medical, a new language style — and accuracy drops. Domain adaptation closes that gap with additional training on target-domain data, sometimes without labels. The subtlety is doing it without erasing the general capabilities that made the base model useful.', 'How you turn a general model into a specialist for your industry’s vocabulary and quirks.', 'Adjusting a model to a target data distribution that differs from its source training distribution.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('replaybuffer', 'Replay Buffer', 'Experience Replay', '', ARRAY['replay buffer','experience replay']::text[], 'Core', 'A stash of old examples the model keeps revisiting so it doesn’t forget them while learning new ones.', 'Mixing a few old flashcards into every study session so you don’t lose what you learned last month.', 'While teaching a model new topics, the trainer sprinkles in old data from the buffer so past skills stay sharp.', '[{"text":"A tool against catastrophic forgetting.","id":"catastrophicforgetting"},{"text":"Common in continual learning.","id":"continuallearning"},{"text":"Also core to reinforcement learning.","id":"reinforcementlearning"}]'::jsonb, 'A replay buffer stores past experiences or examples and re-injects samples of them into ongoing training. In continual learning it preserves old knowledge; in reinforcement learning it also breaks correlations between consecutive samples, making updates more stable. The design questions are what to keep and how to sample from it.', 'A practical guardrail so updating the model doesn’t silently degrade the things it already did well.', 'A memory of prior samples replayed during training to stabilize learning and counter forgetting.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('syntheticbootstrapping', 'Synthetic Bootstrapping', '', '', ARRAY['synthetic bootstrapping','bootstrapping data']::text[], 'Rising', 'Use a model to generate its own training data, then train on it to get better at generating more.', 'Pulling yourself up by your bootstraps — a small start that generates the fuel for a bigger climb.', 'A model writes thousands of math solutions, you keep only the ones that check out, and fine-tune on those to boost it.', '[{"text":"Produces synthetic data.","id":"syntheticdata"},{"text":"Filtered by rejection sampling.","id":"rejectionsampling"},{"text":"A cousin of self-distillation.","id":"selfdistillation"}]'::jsonb, 'Starting from a small seed of quality data or a decent base model, you generate new examples, filter them for correctness, and train on the survivors — then repeat, each round raising the floor. It works best when you can cheaply verify outputs (math, code, tests). The danger is compounding the model’s own errors when your filter is weak.', 'A way to grow training data without armies of human labelers — as long as you can check quality automatically.', 'Iterative self-generation of training data with a verification filter to bootstrap capability gains.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('distillationdataset', 'Distillation Dataset', '', '', ARRAY['distillation dataset','distillation data']::text[], 'Rising', 'A pile of a bigger model’s answers, used as the textbook to teach a smaller model to imitate it.', 'A recording of a master chef cooking, handed to an apprentice to study move for move.', 'A team prompts a large model with 100k questions, saves its responses, and trains a small cheap model on that transcript.', '[{"text":"The fuel for knowledge distillation.","id":"knowledgedistillation"},{"text":"From a teacher to a student model.","id":"teachermodel"},{"text":"A kind of synthetic data.","id":"syntheticdata"}]'::jsonb, 'Rather than distilling from a teacher’s internal probabilities, you often just collect its outputs — questions paired with the big model’s answers — and treat that as a training set for a smaller student. Quality depends entirely on the teacher and the prompts you chose. It’s cheap and effective, though the student inherits the teacher’s mistakes and blind spots too.', 'How a small, cheap model gets much of a big model’s quality — by learning from its answers.', 'A corpus of teacher-model outputs used as supervised targets to train a smaller student.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('transformer', 'Transformer', '', '', ARRAY['transformer','transformers']::text[], 'Core', 'The architecture behind nearly every modern language model — it reads a whole sequence at once using attention.', 'A reader who can glance at every word on the page simultaneously instead of one at a time.', 'GPT, Claude, and BERT are all transformers under the hood, stacking attention layers to process text.', '[{"text":"Its core mechanism.","id":"attention"},{"text":"What it replaced.","id":"recurrentneuralnetwork"},{"text":"Built from encoder and decoder blocks.","id":"encoderdecoder"}]'::jsonb, 'Introduced in 2017, the transformer ditched the step-by-step recurrence of earlier models for attention, which lets every position look at every other position in parallel. That parallelism is why transformers scale so well on modern hardware. Stack enough of these layers, train on enough text, and you get today’s large language models.', 'The foundational design that made large language models practical to train at scale — the “T” in GPT.', 'An attention-based architecture that processes sequences in parallel, stacking self-attention and feed-forward layers.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('attention', 'Attention', '', '', ARRAY['attention','attention mechanism']::text[], 'Core', 'The mechanism that lets a model decide which other words to focus on when interpreting each word.', 'Reading “it” in a sentence and instinctively glancing back to figure out what “it” refers to.', 'To resolve “the trophy didn’t fit in the suitcase because it was too big,” attention links “it” to “trophy.”', '[{"text":"The engine of the transformer.","id":"transformer"},{"text":"The version inside one sequence.","id":"selfattention"},{"text":"Built from queries, keys, and values.","id":"querykeyvalue"}]'::jsonb, 'Attention computes, for each token, a set of weights over all other tokens — how much each one matters right now — and blends their information accordingly. Those weights are learned and context-dependent, so the same word attends differently depending on its neighbors. It’s the idea that unlocked long-range understanding in language models.', 'The breakthrough that let models track meaning across a whole passage instead of just nearby words.', 'A weighted aggregation over token representations where weights come from query-key similarity.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('selfattention', 'Self-Attention', '', '', ARRAY['self-attention','self attention']::text[], 'Core', 'Attention a sequence pays to itself — each word looking at the other words in the same sentence.', 'Everyone at a meeting table turning to hear whoever’s most relevant to the current point.', 'In one sentence, self-attention lets “bank” attend to “river” nearby and settle on the water meaning, not money.', '[{"text":"A specific use of attention.","id":"attention"},{"text":"Contrast with cross-attention.","id":"crossattention"},{"text":"The core of the transformer.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'In self-attention, the queries, keys, and values all come from the same sequence, so every token gathers context from every other token in that same input. Stacking many self-attention layers lets meaning propagate and combine across the whole passage. It’s the workhorse operation inside every transformer block.', 'What lets a model understand a word in the context of the whole message around it.', 'Attention where queries, keys, and values derive from one sequence, mixing information within it.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('crossattention', 'Cross-Attention', '', '', ARRAY['cross-attention','cross attention']::text[], 'Core', 'Attention from one sequence to a different one — letting an output peek at a separate input.', 'A translator reading the original sentence while writing each word of the translation.', 'In a translation model, each output word cross-attends to the source sentence to stay faithful to it.', '[{"text":"Contrast with self-attention.","id":"selfattention"},{"text":"Bridges an encoder and decoder.","id":"encoderdecoder"},{"text":"A form of attention.","id":"attention"}]'::jsonb, 'Cross-attention draws its queries from one sequence but its keys and values from another, so the first sequence conditions on the second. It’s how a decoder consults an encoder’s representation of the input, or how a model grounds generation in retrieved documents or an image. It’s the same math as self-attention, just pointed at a different source.', 'The mechanism that lets a model’s output stay anchored to a separate input like a document or image.', 'Attention where queries come from one sequence and keys/values from another, conditioning one on the other.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('multiheadattention', 'Multi-Head Attention', 'MHA', '', ARRAY['multi-head attention','multihead attention','mha']::text[], 'Core', 'Run attention several times in parallel, each “head” focusing on a different kind of relationship.', 'A panel of specialists reading the same document — one tracks grammar, one tracks tone, one tracks facts.', 'One head links pronouns to nouns while another tracks verb tense, and their views get combined each layer.', '[{"text":"Parallel copies of attention.","id":"attention"},{"text":"Each one is an attention head.","id":"attentionhead"},{"text":"Slimmed down by grouped-query attention.","id":"groupedqueryattention"}]'::jsonb, 'A single attention pattern can only capture one type of relationship at a time. Multi-head attention splits the representation into several subspaces and runs attention independently in each, then concatenates the results. This lets the model attend to many kinds of structure — syntax, coreference, position — simultaneously, and it’s standard in every transformer.', 'Why a model can juggle several kinds of context at once rather than fixating on a single pattern.', 'Parallel attention over projected subspaces whose outputs are concatenated and mixed.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('feedforwardnetwork', 'Feed-Forward Network', 'FFN, MLP', '', ARRAY['feed-forward network','feedforward network','ffn','mlp']::text[], 'Core', 'The little per-word processing block that sits after attention in every transformer layer.', 'After a meeting where everyone shares notes, each person goes to their desk to think it over alone.', 'Following each attention step, the FFN transforms every token’s vector independently before the next layer.', '[{"text":"Pairs with attention in each layer.","id":"attention"},{"text":"A building block of the transformer.","id":"transformer"},{"text":"Uses an activation function.","id":"activationfunction"}]'::jsonb, 'Each transformer layer has two parts: attention mixes information across tokens, then a feed-forward network processes each token on its own through a couple of linear layers with a nonlinearity between them. The FFN holds a large share of the model’s parameters and is where much of its stored knowledge is thought to live. Mixture-of-experts models make this block sparse.', 'Where much of a model’s raw “knowledge capacity” sits — and a big chunk of its parameter count.', 'A position-wise two-layer MLP with a nonlinearity, applied identically to each token after attention.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('residualconnection', 'Residual Connection', 'Skip Connection', '', ARRAY['residual connection','residual connections']::text[], 'Core', 'A shortcut that adds a layer’s input to its output, so information can skip past if needed.', 'Keeping a photocopy of your draft before edits, so nothing important gets lost in revision.', 'In each transformer block, the input is added back to what attention produced, keeping gradients healthy in deep stacks.', '[{"text":"Also called a skip connection.","id":"skipconnection"},{"text":"Paired with layer normalization.","id":"layernormalization"},{"text":"Essential to deep networks.","id":"deeplearning"}]'::jsonb, 'Very deep networks are hard to train because signals and gradients fade as they pass through many layers. A residual connection adds a layer’s input straight to its output, giving information a clear path forward and gradients a clear path back. This one trick is what made training networks with dozens or hundreds of layers practical.', 'A quiet structural trick that made very deep, capable models trainable in the first place.', 'An additive identity shortcut around a sublayer that preserves signal and eases gradient flow.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('skipconnection', 'Skip Connection', '', '', ARRAY['skip connection','skip connections']::text[], 'Core', 'The general name for wiring that lets a signal jump over one or more layers instead of passing through them.', 'An express lane that skips a few local stops so passengers can bypass congestion.', 'U-Nets and transformers alike use skip connections so early features reach later layers untouched.', '[{"text":"The residual add is one kind.","id":"residualconnection"},{"text":"A staple of deep learning.","id":"deeplearning"}]'::jsonb, 'Skip connection is the umbrella term for any path that routes information around intermediate layers; the residual connection — adding input to output — is its most common form. These shortcuts preserve detail that deep stacks would otherwise blur and keep gradients from vanishing. They show up across many architectures, not just transformers.', 'A foundational design idea that keeps deep models both trainable and detail-preserving.', 'Any bypass path routing activations around layers, most often an additive residual.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('encoder', 'Encoder', '', '', ARRAY['encoder','encoders']::text[], 'Core', 'The half of a model that reads an input and compresses it into a rich internal representation.', 'A note-taker who listens to a whole speech and writes a dense summary others can work from.', 'BERT is encoder-only: it reads a sentence and produces vectors great for classification or search, not generation.', '[{"text":"Pairs with a decoder.","id":"decoder"},{"text":"Together they form encoder-decoder.","id":"encoderdecoder"},{"text":"Produces a representation.","id":"representation"}]'::jsonb, 'An encoder maps an input sequence into a set of context-rich vectors, seeing the whole input at once (bidirectionally). It’s ideal when you need to understand or embed text rather than produce more of it — search, classification, retrieval. Encoder-only models like BERT dominate those tasks; pure generation uses decoders instead.', 'The right shape when the job is understanding or searching text, not writing it.', 'A stack that maps input tokens to contextual representations, typically with bidirectional attention.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('decoder', 'Decoder', '', '', ARRAY['decoder','decoders','decoder-only','decoder only']::text[], 'Core', 'The half of a model that generates output one token at a time, each based on what came before.', 'A writer producing a sentence word by word, each choice shaped by everything already written.', 'GPT and Claude are decoder-only models: they read your prompt and generate the continuation token by token.', '[{"text":"The counterpart to an encoder.","id":"encoder"},{"text":"Generates autoregressively.","id":"autoregressive"},{"text":"Uses causal attention.","id":"causalattention"}]'::jsonb, 'A decoder produces tokens sequentially, and to keep generation honest it uses causal (masked) attention so each position can see only earlier tokens, never future ones. Most of today’s large language models are decoder-only — a single stack that both reads the prompt and writes the answer. It’s the architecture built for generation.', 'The shape behind chat and text-generation models — read a prompt, write a continuation.', 'A stack that generates tokens autoregressively using causally-masked self-attention.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('encoderdecoder', 'Encoder-Decoder', 'Seq2Seq', '', ARRAY['encoder-decoder','encoder decoder','seq2seq','sequence to sequence']::text[], 'Core', 'A two-part design where one stack reads the input and another writes the output, linked by attention.', 'A translator with a listening phase and a speaking phase — understand fully first, then produce.', 'T5 and classic translation models use this: the encoder digests the source, the decoder emits the translation.', '[{"text":"Combines an encoder and decoder.","id":"encoder"},{"text":"Linked via cross-attention.","id":"crossattention"},{"text":"The original transformer shape.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'The original transformer was encoder-decoder: the encoder builds a representation of the input, and the decoder generates the output while cross-attending to that representation. It fits tasks with a clear input-to-output mapping like translation or summarization. Many modern chat models skip the encoder and go decoder-only, but the two-part design still shines for structured transduction.', 'The classic fit for “turn this input into that output” tasks like translation and summarization.', 'An architecture pairing a bidirectional encoder with an autoregressive decoder joined by cross-attention.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('attentionhead', 'Attention Head', '', '', ARRAY['attention head','attention heads']::text[], 'Core', 'One independent attention computation inside a layer, specializing in a particular kind of relationship.', 'A single lane of traffic among several — each carries its own flow, all part of one highway.', 'Researchers have found individual heads that track subject-verb agreement or copy the previous token.', '[{"text":"Many heads make multi-head attention.","id":"multiheadattention"},{"text":"Each computes attention.","id":"attention"}]'::jsonb, 'A head is one slice of multi-head attention: it projects tokens into its own subspace and computes its own attention pattern. Different heads learn to specialize — some track position, some syntax, some coreference — and interpretability research often studies individual heads to understand what a model has learned. Modern efficiency tricks share keys and values across heads to save memory.', 'The unit researchers poke at to understand what a model actually pays attention to.', 'A single attention operation over one projected subspace within multi-head attention.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('querykeyvalue', 'Query, Key, Value', 'QKV', '', ARRAY['query key value','qkv','queries keys values']::text[], 'Core', 'The three roles each token plays in attention: what it’s looking for, what it offers, and what it hands over.', 'A library search: your query, each book’s label (key), and the book’s actual contents (value).', 'A token’s query is matched against every token’s key; the closest matches decide whose values get blended in.', '[{"text":"The inputs to attention.","id":"attention"},{"text":"Matched via scaled dot-product attention.","id":"scaleddotproductattention"},{"text":"Keys and values get cached.","id":"kvcache"}]'::jsonb, 'Attention derives three vectors from each token. The query says what this token wants; keys advertise what every token contains; the dot-product of a query with each key gives relevance scores; those scores then weight the values that get summed into the output. This query-key-value framing is the machinery underneath every attention mechanism.', 'The conceptual gears of attention — worth knowing when you hear about KV caching and its memory costs.', 'The three learned projections per token whose query-key similarity weights a sum over values.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('scaleddotproductattention', 'Scaled Dot-Product Attention', '', '', ARRAY['scaled dot-product attention','scaled dot product attention']::text[], 'Core', 'The exact recipe for attention: score with dot products, shrink the scores, softmax, then blend.', 'Rating each option, dividing the scores to keep them sane, turning them into percentages, then mixing accordingly.', 'Each query dots against all keys, the scores are divided by the square root of the dimension, softmaxed, and applied to values.', '[{"text":"The concrete form of attention.","id":"attention"},{"text":"Operates on query, key, value.","id":"querykeyvalue"},{"text":"Uses a softmax.","id":"softmax"}]'::jsonb, 'The “scaled” part matters: raw dot products grow with vector dimension, pushing softmax into saturated regions where gradients vanish. Dividing by the square root of the key dimension keeps scores in a workable range. After softmax turns them into weights, you take the weighted sum of values. This precise formula is the beating heart of the transformer.', 'The standard, well-understood formula that every attention layer runs — rarely something you tune directly.', 'Attention as softmax(QKᵀ/√d)·V, with √d scaling to stabilize gradients.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('maskedattention', 'Masked Attention', '', '', ARRAY['masked attention','attention masking']::text[], 'Core', 'Attention with certain positions deliberately hidden, so the model can’t look where it shouldn’t.', 'Covering the answers below a quiz question so you can only use what’s above it.', 'A text generator masks future tokens so, while predicting word five, it can’t peek at words six and beyond.', '[{"text":"The causal case is causal attention.","id":"causalattention"},{"text":"Implemented with an attention mask.","id":"attentionmask"},{"text":"Used in the decoder.","id":"decoder"}]'::jsonb, 'Masking sets certain attention scores to negative infinity before the softmax so those positions get zero weight. The most common use is causal masking in decoders — hiding future tokens to preserve the left-to-right generation setup — but masks also ignore padding or enforce custom visibility patterns. It’s a simple, powerful lever over what each token can see.', 'The guardrail that keeps a generative model from cheating by seeing the answer it’s supposed to predict.', 'Attention with selected scores set to −∞ pre-softmax to zero out disallowed positions.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('causalattention', 'Causal Attention', 'Autoregressive Masking', '', ARRAY['causal attention','causal masking','autoregressive masking']::text[], 'Core', 'Attention where every token can see the past and present but never the future.', 'Writing a story where you can reread earlier pages but the next ones haven’t been written yet.', 'In GPT-style generation, causal attention ensures token five is predicted from tokens one through four only.', '[{"text":"A specific masked attention.","id":"maskedattention"},{"text":"Enables autoregressive generation.","id":"autoregressive"},{"text":"Defines the decoder.","id":"decoder"}]'::jsonb, 'Causal attention applies a triangular mask so position i attends only to positions ≤ i. This enforces the autoregressive assumption — predict the next token from prior context — and lets training on a full sequence teach every next-token prediction at once. It’s the reason decoder-only language models can be trained efficiently and generate coherently.', 'The rule that makes left-to-right text generation consistent between training and real use.', 'Triangular masking restricting each position to attend only to itself and earlier positions.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('mixtureofexperts', 'Mixture of Experts', 'MoE', '', ARRAY['mixture of experts','moe']::text[], 'Rising', 'Split a model into many specialist sub-networks and route each token to just a few of them.', 'A hospital where a receptionist sends each patient to the two right specialists instead of every doctor at once.', 'A model has 64 expert blocks but activates only two per token, so it’s huge in capacity yet cheap to run.', '[{"text":"Makes the feed-forward network sparse.","id":"feedforwardnetwork"},{"text":"A sparse model design.","id":"sparsemodel"},{"text":"Contrast with a dense model.","id":"densemodel"}]'::jsonb, 'In a mixture-of-experts layer, a lightweight router picks a small subset of expert sub-networks to process each token, so total parameters can be enormous while compute per token stays modest. The wins are capacity and efficiency; the headaches are load-balancing the experts, routing instability, and the memory to hold all those parameters. It powers several frontier models.', 'How models get much bigger in capability without a proportional jump in inference cost.', 'A layer that routes each token to a few of many expert subnetworks, decoupling parameter count from per-token compute.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('sparseattention', 'Sparse Attention', '', '', ARRAY['sparse attention']::text[], 'Rising', 'Attention that only connects each token to a chosen subset of others instead of all of them.', 'Instead of everyone at a huge conference talking to everyone, people only chat with their nearest neighbors and a few leaders.', 'For a very long document, a model attends to nearby tokens plus a few global ones rather than the full quadratic grid.', '[{"text":"A cheaper form of attention.","id":"attention"},{"text":"Relatives include sliding window attention.","id":"slidingwindowattention"},{"text":"Helps with long context.","id":"contextlength"}]'::jsonb, 'Full attention costs grow with the square of sequence length, which gets brutal for long inputs. Sparse attention restricts each token to a limited pattern of connections — local windows, strided jumps, a handful of global tokens — cutting the cost while trying to preserve the connections that matter. The art is choosing a sparsity pattern that keeps quality high.', 'A key enabler of long-context models that would otherwise be too expensive to run.', 'Attention restricted to a structured subset of token pairs to reduce quadratic cost.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('flashattention', 'Flash Attention', '', '', ARRAY['flash attention','flashattention']::text[], 'Rising', 'A faster, memory-frugal way to compute exact attention by being clever about how the GPU moves data.', 'Cooking straight from the counter instead of walking to the pantry for each ingredient — same dish, far less trips.', 'Swapping in flash attention lets a team train on longer sequences at the same speed, with no change to the results.', '[{"text":"A faster computation of attention.","id":"attention"},{"text":"Speeds up training.","id":"training"},{"text":"Helps enable long context.","id":"contextlength"}]'::jsonb, 'Standard attention writes a giant scores matrix to slow GPU memory and reads it back — the real bottleneck. Flash attention tiles the computation so intermediate values stay in fast on-chip memory, computing the same exact result without ever materializing the full matrix. The output is identical; the speed and memory savings are large, which is why it’s become the default.', 'An under-the-hood efficiency win that made longer contexts and cheaper training practical.', 'An IO-aware, tiled exact-attention kernel that avoids materializing the full attention matrix in HBM.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('slidingwindowattention', 'Sliding Window Attention', '', '', ARRAY['sliding window attention','local attention']::text[], 'Rising', 'Each token only attends to a fixed window of nearby tokens, keeping long sequences affordable.', 'Reading with a ruler under the line — you focus on the words right around you, not the whole page at once.', 'A model uses a 4,000-token window so processing a 100,000-token document stays linear instead of exploding.', '[{"text":"A form of sparse attention.","id":"sparseattention"},{"text":"Trades global reach for efficiency in attention.","id":"attention"},{"text":"Enables longer context.","id":"contextlength"}]'::jsonb, 'Sliding window attention limits each token’s view to a local neighborhood of fixed size, making cost grow linearly with length rather than quadratically. Information still travels far because stacking layers lets windows overlap and propagate — like ripples reaching across the sequence over several hops. Many long-context models pair it with a few global tokens for the rest.', 'A practical way to stretch context length without the cost blowing up.', 'Local attention over a fixed-size window per token, giving linear cost with multi-layer receptive-field growth.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('groupedqueryattention', 'Grouped-Query Attention', 'GQA', '', ARRAY['grouped-query attention','grouped query attention','gqa']::text[], 'Rising', 'Let several attention heads share one set of keys and values to shrink memory during generation.', 'A few coworkers sharing one filing cabinet instead of each keeping a full duplicate set of folders.', 'A model gives 32 query heads but only 8 shared key-value groups, cutting the memory its KV cache needs.', '[{"text":"A middle ground for multi-head attention.","id":"multiheadattention"},{"text":"The extreme case is multi-query attention.","id":"multiqueryattention"},{"text":"Shrinks the KV cache.","id":"kvcache"}]'::jsonb, 'The KV cache — stored keys and values for every past token — dominates memory during long generations. Multi-query attention shares a single key-value set across all heads (fast, but can hurt quality); grouped-query attention is the compromise, letting groups of query heads share key-value sets. It keeps most of the quality while sharply reducing cache size and bandwidth.', 'A quiet efficiency choice that makes long-context serving cheaper and faster.', 'Attention where query heads are grouped to share key/value projections, shrinking KV-cache footprint.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('multiqueryattention', 'Multi-Query Attention', 'MQA', '', ARRAY['multi-query attention','multi query attention','mqa']::text[], 'Rising', 'All attention heads share a single set of keys and values — the most aggressive memory-saving variant.', 'The whole office sharing one filing cabinet — lean and fast, but everyone competes for the same drawers.', 'An inference-optimized model uses one key-value head for all query heads to make its KV cache as small as possible.', '[{"text":"The extreme of grouped-query attention.","id":"groupedqueryattention"},{"text":"A variant of multi-head attention.","id":"multiheadattention"},{"text":"Minimizes the KV cache.","id":"kvcache"}]'::jsonb, 'Multi-query attention keeps many query heads but collapses to a single shared key and value head, minimizing the KV cache and the memory bandwidth needed each generation step. That makes decoding notably faster, at some cost to quality. Grouped-query attention emerged as the popular middle ground, recovering most of the lost quality while keeping much of the speed.', 'A serving-speed optimization that trades a little quality for cheaper, faster generation.', 'Attention with a single shared key/value head across all query heads, minimizing KV-cache size.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('kvcache', 'KV Cache', 'Key-Value Cache', '', ARRAY['kv cache','key-value cache','kv caching']::text[], 'Core', 'Stored keys and values from earlier tokens so the model doesn’t recompute them every generation step.', 'Keeping your running notes open so you don’t reread the whole book each time you write a new line.', 'While generating a long reply, the model caches each token’s keys and values so step 500 doesn’t redo steps 1–499.', '[{"text":"Caches attention’s keys and values.","id":"querykeyvalue"},{"text":"Shrunk by grouped-query attention.","id":"groupedqueryattention"},{"text":"A cost during inference.","id":"inference"}]'::jsonb, 'Autoregressive generation would be wildly wasteful if each new token recomputed attention over the entire history. The KV cache stores the keys and values of all previous tokens so each step only computes the new one and attends against the cache. The trade-off is memory: the cache grows with sequence length and batch size, which is exactly what GQA and MQA aim to tame.', 'The reason long conversations get memory-hungry — and a big driver of serving cost.', 'Cached per-token keys/values reused across decoding steps, trading memory for avoided recomputation.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('rotaryembeddings', 'Rotary Embeddings', 'RoPE', '', ARRAY['rotary embeddings','rotary position embedding','rope']::text[], 'Rising', 'Encode a token’s position by rotating its vector, so relative distances fall out naturally in attention.', 'Turning each clock hand by an amount set by the hour — the angle between hands tells you the gap.', 'A model uses RoPE so that “word 10 relative to word 7” is captured cleanly, and it extends to longer inputs gracefully.', '[{"text":"A modern positional embedding.","id":"positionalembedding"},{"text":"An alternative is ALiBi.","id":"alibi"},{"text":"Shapes attention.","id":"attention"}]'::jsonb, 'RoPE injects position by rotating each token’s query and key vectors by an angle proportional to their position. Because attention compares queries and keys via dot products, these rotations make the score depend on the relative distance between tokens — a clean, position-aware signal. It also extends to longer sequences than seen in training better than older schemes, which is why it’s now common.', 'Part of why modern models handle long inputs and relative word order so well.', 'Position encoding via rotation of query/key vectors, yielding relative-position-aware dot products.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('alibi', 'ALiBi', 'Attention with Linear Biases', '', ARRAY['alibi','attention with linear biases']::text[], 'Fading', 'Add a small distance-based penalty to attention scores so far-away tokens matter a little less.', 'A conversation where voices from across the room come through fainter the farther away they are.', 'A model trained with ALiBi on short sequences still works on much longer ones at inference without retraining.', '[{"text":"An alternative to rotary embeddings.","id":"rotaryembeddings"},{"text":"A kind of positional embedding.","id":"positionalembedding"},{"text":"Biases attention.","id":"attention"}]'::jsonb, 'Instead of adding position vectors, ALiBi subtracts a penalty from each attention score proportional to how far apart the two tokens are. This bakes in a “nearer matters more” prior and, notably, lets models generalize to sequences longer than those seen in training. It was influential for long-context work, though rotary embeddings have become the more common default.', 'An early trick for length generalization, now largely overtaken by rotary embeddings.', 'Position handling via a linear distance penalty added to attention logits, aiding length extrapolation.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('positionalembedding', 'Positional Embedding', '', '', ARRAY['positional embedding','learned position embedding']::text[], 'Core', 'Extra information that tells the model where each token sits, since attention alone ignores order.', 'Numbering the pages of a manuscript before shuffling them, so the order can always be recovered.', 'Without positional info, “dog bites man” and “man bites dog” look identical to attention — embeddings fix that.', '[{"text":"Modern versions include rotary embeddings.","id":"rotaryembeddings"},{"text":"And ALiBi.","id":"alibi"},{"text":"Compare positional encoding.","id":"positionalencoding"}]'::jsonb, 'Attention is order-blind: it treats its inputs as a set, so without positional signals a transformer can’t tell sequence order. Positional embeddings supply that missing structure, either learned per position or computed by a fixed function, and are added to or folded into token representations. Which scheme you pick strongly affects how well the model handles long or unusual-length inputs.', 'The mechanism that lets an order-blind architecture understand word order at all.', 'Signals encoding token position added to or combined with embeddings to restore sequence order.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('convolutionalneuralnetwork', 'Convolutional Neural Network', 'CNN, ConvNet', '', ARRAY['convolutional neural network','cnn','convnet']::text[], 'Core', 'A network that scans small patches across an input to detect local patterns, great for images.', 'Sliding a magnifying glass across a photo, noting edges and textures wherever it lands.', 'A CNN powers a phone’s photo classifier, spotting edges, then shapes, then whole objects layer by layer.', '[{"text":"A pillar of deep learning.","id":"deeplearning"},{"text":"For sequences, compare the recurrent neural network.","id":"recurrentneuralnetwork"},{"text":"Largely supplanted for text by the transformer.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'CNNs apply small learnable filters that slide across the input, reusing the same weights everywhere so they detect a pattern wherever it appears. Stacked layers build from simple features (edges) to complex ones (faces). They dominated computer vision for years and remain strong there, though transformers have encroached on vision too. For text and long-range reasoning, transformers took over.', 'The workhorse behind most image-recognition features of the last decade.', 'A network of shared-weight sliding filters exploiting spatial locality and translation invariance.', 'Architectures', 80, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('recurrentneuralnetwork', 'Recurrent Neural Network', 'RNN', '', ARRAY['recurrent neural network','rnn']::text[], 'Fading', 'A network that reads a sequence one step at a time, carrying a memory of what it has seen so far.', 'Reading a sentence word by word while keeping a running gist of it in your head.', 'Before transformers, RNNs handled translation and speech by processing text left to right, updating a hidden state.', '[{"text":"Improved by the LSTM.","id":"lstm"},{"text":"And the GRU.","id":"gru"},{"text":"Largely replaced by the transformer.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'An RNN maintains a hidden state updated at each timestep, letting information flow forward through a sequence. That sequential dependency is also its weakness: it can’t parallelize across time, and long-range signals fade or explode through many steps. Gated variants like LSTM and GRU helped, but attention-based transformers ultimately outscaled them and pushed RNNs to the margins.', 'The prior era’s approach to sequence modeling, now mostly of historical and niche interest.', 'A network with a recurrent hidden state updated per timestep, limited by sequential compute and vanishing gradients.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('lstm', 'LSTM', 'Long Short-Term Memory', '', ARRAY['lstm','long short-term memory']::text[], 'Fading', 'A recurrent network with gates that decide what to remember and forget, so it can hold information longer.', 'A notepad with an eraser and a highlighter — you keep the important lines and clear the rest as you go.', 'Before transformers, LSTMs powered much of machine translation and speech recognition for years.', '[{"text":"A gated recurrent neural network.","id":"recurrentneuralnetwork"},{"text":"A simpler cousin is the GRU.","id":"gru"},{"text":"Superseded by the transformer.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'The LSTM added input, forget, and output gates plus a protected cell state, giving gradients a stable path through time and letting the network retain information across longer spans than a plain RNN. It was the dominant sequence model of the 2010s. Transformers eventually beat it on scale and parallelism, but the LSTM’s gating ideas still echo in newer architectures.', 'The reliable sequence model of the pre-transformer era — historically pivotal, now rarely the default.', 'A gated recurrent unit with a cell state and forget/input/output gates that mitigate vanishing gradients.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('gru', 'GRU', 'Gated Recurrent Unit', '', ARRAY['gru','gated recurrent unit']::text[], 'Fading', 'A streamlined LSTM with fewer gates — nearly as capable, a bit cheaper and simpler.', 'A lighter backpack with one fewer pocket that still carries almost everything you need.', 'A team on a tight compute budget picks a GRU over an LSTM for a sequence task and loses little accuracy.', '[{"text":"A simpler LSTM.","id":"lstm"},{"text":"A gated recurrent neural network.","id":"recurrentneuralnetwork"},{"text":"Overtaken by the transformer.","id":"transformer"}]'::jsonb, 'The GRU merges the LSTM’s gates into two (update and reset) and drops the separate cell state, making it lighter and faster to train while often matching LSTM performance. It was a popular choice when efficiency mattered. Like the LSTM, it belongs to the recurrent era that transformers largely displaced, though it remains a clean baseline for small sequence problems.', 'A lighter alternative to the LSTM from the same era — simple and efficient, but no longer the go-to.', 'A recurrent unit with update/reset gates and no separate cell state, cheaper than an LSTM at similar quality.', 'Architectures', 30, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('statespacemodel', 'State Space Model', 'SSM', '', ARRAY['state space model','ssm']::text[], 'Rising', 'A sequence model that carries a compact running state, mixing RNN-like memory with parallel training.', 'A thermostat that tracks a single evolving reading over time instead of re-reading the whole day’s log.', 'For very long sequences, an SSM keeps a fixed-size state so cost grows linearly, not quadratically like attention.', '[{"text":"A prominent example is Mamba.","id":"mamba"},{"text":"An alternative to the transformer.","id":"transformer"},{"text":"Descends from recurrent ideas.","id":"recurrentneuralnetwork"}]'::jsonb, 'State space models process sequences through a linear dynamical system: a hidden state evolves step to step, summarizing history in fixed size. Cleverly, they can be computed either recurrently (cheap at inference) or as a convolution (parallel at training), sidestepping the RNN’s training bottleneck. Their linear scaling with length makes them attractive for very long contexts where attention gets expensive.', 'A promising challenger to attention for very long inputs, with cheaper scaling.', 'A linear-recurrence sequence model with a fixed-size state, computable as convolution for parallel training.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('mamba', 'Mamba', '', '', ARRAY['mamba']::text[], 'Rising', 'A state space model that adds input-dependent control, rivaling transformers with linear-time scaling.', 'A thermostat smart enough to change how hard it reacts based on what’s happening right now.', 'Mamba handles very long sequences at lower cost than attention while staying competitive on language tasks.', '[{"text":"A selective state space model.","id":"statespacemodel"},{"text":"Competes with the transformer.","id":"transformer"},{"text":"Another recurrent-style challenger is RWKV.","id":"rwkv"}]'::jsonb, 'Mamba’s key move is making the state space model’s parameters depend on the input — “selective” state spaces — so the model can choose what to remember or ignore per token, something earlier SSMs couldn’t. Combined with a hardware-aware implementation, it achieves linear scaling in sequence length while matching transformers on many tasks. It’s a leading example of the post-attention exploration.', 'A live bet that not every strong model has to be a transformer — especially for long sequences.', 'A selective SSM with input-dependent dynamics and a hardware-aware scan, giving linear-time sequence modeling.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[]),
  ('rwkv', 'RWKV', '', '', ARRAY['rwkv']::text[], 'Rising', 'An architecture that trains like a transformer but runs like an RNN, aiming for the best of both.', 'A hybrid car — plug-in convenience for the long haul, efficient engine for the daily drive.', 'RWKV lets a long chat run with constant memory per token, unlike a transformer’s growing KV cache.', '[{"text":"Blends the transformer and recurrent neural network.","id":"transformer"},{"text":"A linear-scaling peer to Mamba.","id":"mamba"},{"text":"Related to state space models.","id":"statespacemodel"}]'::jsonb, 'RWKV reformulates attention-like mixing into a recurrent form that can be trained in parallel like a transformer but executed step by step like an RNN, giving constant memory and linear time at inference. That makes very long or streaming generation cheap in memory. It’s part of the wave of architectures probing whether quadratic attention is truly necessary.', 'Another contender for cheap long-context and streaming use, trading the transformer’s memory growth for a constant footprint.', 'A linear-attention-style architecture with parallel training and RNN-like constant-memory inference.', 'Architectures', 60, ARRAY['seed','architectures']::text[])
